So what is the effect we want here? how is the `ngenApplications` exactly used?

@JanKrivanek It's not well documented beyond [what's in our repo](https://github.com/dotnet/msbuild/blob/main/documentation/NETFramework-NGEN.md#ngen-in-visual-studio), but if you just say "ngen this assembly" in a .swr, it is interpreted to mean "ngen this assembly in the context of `vsn.exe`, the generated `devenv.exe.config`". That is appropriate for many assemblies, including MSBuild, but not everything, so there's a way to instead specify a list of `ngenApplications`, `.exe` paths within VS that we'll be ngened for (basically `ngen install {dll} /execonfig:{exe}` as shown in the logs above).

For MSBuild, we want our core assemblies ngened in several contexts:

* `vsn.exe`, that is in-proc in VS, in amd64 (or ARM64) context
* `bin\amd64\MSBuild.exe`, 64-bit MSBuild, in 64-bit mode
* `bin\arm64\MSBuild.exe`, ARM64 MSBuild, if applicable
* `bin\MSBuild.exe`, 32-bit MSBuild, in 32-bit

The last one is the "for compat" option: it's not used by default (VS is amd64 and so is the default `MSBuild.exe` on PATH in the developer command prompt). So it's the least important. But it's the context we were specifying for all of our assemblies for the non-VS use cases. This switches to specifying the amd64 one instead since it's more relevant to users.

However, what actually matters at native-image load time is the closure of dependencies and whether the assembly was ngened for the current bitness, not the ngen-time `.exe.config` exactly. Since our different bitness exes have the same dependency closure, specifying any of them should be equivalent--which is why I expected (and validated) that there's no methodsJitted changes resulting from this cleanup.
